  "doc_id": "60485",
  "text": "This group of MMPs includes MMP-1, MMP-8 and MMP-13. These MMPs degrade -helices of interstitial collagen (type I, II, III) at two locations, specifically and fragments, in the place of uncoiled triple-helix (thanks to absence hydroxyproline and higher abundance of hydrophobic groups). Collagenases cleave the 1 chain of collagen type I in sequence Gly775/Ile776 while the 2 chain of collagen type I in Gly775/Leu776 regions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Collagenases differ from other MMPs, in that they are only able to cleave collagen helices in the native state at neutral pH by a nondenaturing mechanism. Collagenases significantly differ in their substrate specificity. Neutrophil collagenases (MMP-8) cleave collagen type I substrates, while interstitial collagenases (MMP-1) cleave collagen type III substrates. Although MMP-3 binds to collagen type I, it does not cleave it [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . MMP-13 cleaves collagen type I and III, but at a slower rate than type II [CITATION_7] .",
